      <div class="SOTTO_PARA"><a name="DUCb9d667d82e5b100581afe23c1c37e99c"></a>Checking the engine oil pressure
      </div>
      <div class="SOTTO_PARA">
         <div class="Testo"><a name="d3e4251"> </a>To carry out this procedure a commercial engine oil pressure tester can be used.
         </div>
      </div>
      <div class="SOTTO_PARA">
         <div class="Testo"><a name="d3e4254"> </a>Oil pressure test values:
         </div>
         <div class="Testo"><a name="d3e4256"> </a>Hot engine (oil temperature at least = 80 °C) 
         </div>
         <div class="Testo"><a name="d3e4258"> </a>1100÷1300 rpm
         </div>
         <div class="Testo"><a name="d3e4261"> </a>greater than 0.8 bar.
         </div>
         <div class="Testo"><a name="d3e4263"> </a>3500÷4000 rpm
         </div>
         <div class="Testo"><a name="d3e4266"> </a>greater than 4 bar.
         </div>
      </div>
      <div class="Attenzione"><img class="Attenzione" width="28" height="25" style="display: inline; float: none; left: 0.0; text-align: left; top: 0.0;" src="img/important.jpg">Important
      </div>
      <div class="Testo"><a name="d3e4269"> </a>The maximum pressure must never exceed 6.0&nbsp;bar.
      </div>
      <div class="SOTTO_PARA">
         <div class="Testo"><a name="d3e4272"> </a>Excessively high pressure may indicate that the relief valve is stuck. Excessively low pressure, on the other hand, may be
            caused&nbsp;by the relief valve being stuck in the open position, the spring being too weak, or a faulty oil pump. Other&nbsp;causes
            are excessively worn seals and gaskets or a badly worn engine.
         </div>
      </div>
